[Mizoram, a state in north eastern India, borders several Indian sister-states as well as the neighbouring countries of Bangladesh and Myanmar. See map at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mizoram#/media/File:IN-MZ.svg.

Porcine reproductive and respiratory syndrome (PRRS), an OIE-reportable disease, is characterised by reproductive failure of sows and respiratory disease in pigs. Initially recognised in 1987 in the United States of America, in 1989 in Japan and in 1990 in Germany, it has since become a pandemic. The disease is caused by the PRRS virus (PRRSV), classified as a member of the order _Nidovirales_, family _Arteriviridae_, genus _Arterivirus_. Apart from domestic pigs, feral swine and wild boars, no other species are known to be naturally infected with PRRSV. The virus does not pose a zoonotic risk and it is not infectious for humans or for cells of human origin.

For further information, please refer to the chapter 2.8.6. of OIE's Manual, at http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Health_standards/tahm/2.08.06_PRRS.pdf (version adopted May 2015).

CSF is regarded endemic in India (the last available information, covering January-June 2017, reports 23 new outbreaks). - Mod.AS

